04858nam a2200781Ia 9780228020141DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280201417 a10.1515/97802280201412doi  a(DE-B1597)679706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aD547.C2bK46 2024eb 7aHIS0271602bisacsh04a940.4/1271qCaOONL223/eng/202308281 aKennedy, Gregory M.W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLost in the Crowd :bAcadian Soldiers of Canada's First World War /cGregory M.W. Kennedy. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource :b18 photos, 10 diagrams, 14 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLa collection Louis J. Robichaud/The Louis J. Robichaud Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tGratitude -- tIntroduction -- t1 Creating an Acadian Battalion, November 1915–June 1916 -- t2 Training, Preparations, and Completing the Battalion, July 1916–March 1917 -- t3 Heading Overseas, March–June 1917 -- t4 Life in the Canadian Forestry Corps, May 1917–November 1918 -- t5 Demobilization and Post-War Transition -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn December 1915, as the First World War wore on, Acadian leaders meeting in New Brunswick deplored how soldiers from their communities were “lost in the crowd” of the Canadian Expeditionary Force. They successfully lobbied the federal government for the creation of an Acadian national unit that would be French-speaking, Catholic, and led by their own. More than a thousand Acadians from across the Maritime provinces, Quebec, and the American northeast answered the call.In Lost in the Crowd Gregory Kennedy draws on military archives, census records, newspapers, and soldiers’ letters to present a new kind of military history focusing on the experiences of Acadian soldiers and their families before, during, and after the war. He shows that Acadians were just as likely to enlist as their English-speaking counterparts across the Maritimes, though the backgrounds of the volunteers were quite different. Kennedy tackles controversial topics often missing from the previous historiography, such as underage recruits, desertion, and army discipline. With the help of the 1921 Canadian Census, he explores the factors that influenced post-war outcomes, both positive and negative, for soldiers, families, and communities.Lost in the Crowd offers a completely new and replicable approach to the traditional regimental history, reconstituting the lives of soldiers and their families. The focus on the Acadians, a francophone minority group in the Maritime provinces, significantly shifts our understanding of French Canada and the First World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAcadiansxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldierszMaritime ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zMaritime Provinces. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh  aAcadia.  aAtlantic Canada.  aCanadian Expeditionary Force.  aCanadian Forestry Corps.  aFirst World War.  aFrance.  aFrancophone.  aFrench Canada.  aJura.  acensuses.  ademobilization.  adiscipline.  aillness.  alongitudinal analysis.  aminority.  anationalism.  areconstitution.  arecruitment.  asoldiers.  atraining.  aveterans.  awork.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311140848440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228020141?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228020141423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228020141/original  a